the 2008/09 economic crisis, which hit our country hard. During the boom times in the middle of the noughties, our citizenship policy robustly opened the doors to many people from all over the world. Thousands of people from new countries became part of our families, this country, and our society.
These people came to our country, not fully understanding our history and our past, which has been quite traumatic in the last 1,000 years. Therefore, in the foundation of the new Icelandic citizenship policy, it was stressed that integration into our society was a two-way street. Exact integration implies more mutual understanding of each other in Icelandic society as well as in the communities where immigrants live and, most importantly, it should be a mutual understanding that neither newcomers nor existing citizens are to blame for the frustration emerging from changes in our societies and in the arduous task of finding new ways of living together after the crisis.
Iceland was governed by the citizens’ party (HiP) prior to 2009, and creating a culture of community in the party was of the utmost importance. The community of the citizens’ party ran the country, from the Foreign minister to local councils. We deliberated very much whether the requirements for Icelandic citizenship should be raised. We stressed that those requirements were so hard and demanding that acquiring Icelandic citizenship was something that only a few people, who really put their heart and soul into it, could achieve.
